        /* FAQ Section EN */
        faq_h1: "Documentation & FAQ",
        faq_subtitle: "Complete guide for PassForge Pro security architecture",
        faq_q1: "How does the Clipboard Sanitation work?",
        faq_a1: "PassForge monitors the system clipboard state. Once a password is copied, a secure background thread starts a countdown. Upon completion, it overwrites the clipboard with empty strings and forces a garbage collection to ensure no forensic traces remain in memory.",
        faq_q2: "What is No-Interaction Auto-Lock?",
        faq_a2: "Our 'Unmanned Defense' protocol tracks user interaction with the GUI. If no mouse or keyboard events are detected within your specified window, the vault is immediately purged and the application returns to a locked state. All active memory keys are shredded.",
        faq_q3: "How secure is the Master Password?",
        faq_a3: "We use PBKDF2 with HMAC-SHA256 and high iteration counts (100,000+). This renders brute-force attacks computationally infeasible on modern hardware, effectively creating a 'Fortress' level security substrate.",
        faq_q4: "Does PassForge resist CPU backdoors (e.g., Intel ME)?",
        faq_a4: "PassForge is hardware-agnostic but memory-sensitive. By using state-free memory protection and minimizing the time encryption keys reside in RAM, we mitigate the risk of Ring-0 or hardware-level logic snooping.",
        faq_q5: "What if the entire system is hacked?",
        faq_a5: "Even in a total OS compromise, your vault remains encrypted. The keys are never stored on disk. Unless the attacker can dump the RAM during the brief seconds the vault is active, the data remains a 256-bit encrypted black box.",
        faq_q6: "Can malware steal data after the vault is locked?",
        faq_a6: "No. Upon locking, the application executes a 'Memory Shred' command. All RAM sectors previously holding plain-text keys or data are overwritten with zeros and flushed. Malware scanning the memory post-lock will find nothing but noise.",
        faq_q7: "Can the master password be captured from RAM when entered?",
        faq_a7: "We mitigate this by using bytearray-based handling where possible and overwriting the RAM sector immediately after key derivation. Minimal persistent state is our core defense.",

