        src_preview_theme4: "preview-en/theme4.png",
        faq_a7: "Theoretically yes, but it requires: (1) Admin/root access on the same machine, (2) Perfect timing during password entry, (3) Targeted memory dump tools. This is an 'evil maid' or insider attack scenario, not a remote threat. The password exists in RAM only briefly during authentication.",
        faq_q8: "What about memory dump + string scan attacks?",
        faq_a8: "The Fernet key is never stored on disk and exists only during runtime. PBKDF2 output is binary and short-lived. If an attacker dumps memory while the vault is unlocked, plaintext data could be visible‚Äîthis is true for all password managers including KeePass and Bitwarden.",
        faq_q9: "Does PyArmor anti-debug really stop reverse engineering?",
        faq_a9: "PyArmor stops casual debuggers and script kiddies. It cannot stop kernel-level memory dumps or professional reverse engineering. However, it significantly raises the cost and time required for analysis, which is the industry-standard approach.",
        faq_q10: "What if the encryption algorithm is discovered?",
        faq_a10: "Modern cryptography does NOT rely on algorithm secrecy (Kerckhoffs's principle). PassForge uses industry-standard AES-256, Fernet, PBKDF2, and bcrypt. Even if the algorithm is known, without your master password and the runtime-generated salt, the data remains secure.",
        faq_q11: "Would running this on Tails increase security?",
        faq_a11: "Yes, significantly. Tails is a RAM-only OS with no disk persistence, no swap, and built-in anti-forensics. Running PassForge on Tails eliminates disk forensics, swap file analysis, and most persistence-based attacks. This is elite-level operational security.",
        faq_q12: "Can someone brute-force my master password?",
        faq_a12: "Extremely unlikely. We use PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA256 with 150,000 iterations + bcrypt with 12 rounds. Even with a GPU cluster, brute-forcing a strong 16+ character password would take centuries. The key derivation is intentionally slow to prevent high-speed attacks.",
        faq_q13: "What happens if I forget my master password?",
        faq_a13: "Your vault is permanently inaccessible. There is NO password recovery, NO backdoor, NO master key. This is by design. The encryption is mathematically unbreakable without the correct password. Always maintain secure offline backups of your master password.",
        faq_q14: "Is the SQLite database file encrypted?",
        faq_a14: "Yes, but with a critical distinction: The database STRUCTURE is visible (tables, columns), but all CONTENT is encrypted with Fernet. An attacker can see you have a 'passwords' table, but cannot read any entries without your master key.",
        faq_q15: "Can PassForge protect against keyloggers?",
        faq_a15: "No password manager can fully protect against kernel-level keyloggers. However, PassForge minimizes exposure: (1) Password is only in RAM briefly, (2) Auto-lock on inactivity, (3) Clipboard auto-clear. For maximum protection, use a hardware security key or virtual keyboard.",
        faq_q16: "What if my vault file is stolen?",
        faq_a16: "The attacker has an encrypted blob. Without your master password, it's computationally infeasible to decrypt. They would need to brute-force PBKDF2 (150k iterations) + bcrypt (12 rounds) + AES-256. With a strong password, this is effectively impossible.",
        faq_q17: "Does PassForge have a cloud sync feature?",
        faq_a17: "No, and this is intentional. Cloud sync introduces attack surface (man-in-the-middle, server breaches, metadata leakage). PassForge is designed for LOCAL-ONLY storage. For multi-device sync, manually transfer the encrypted vault file via secure channels.",
        faq_q18: "Can I audit the source code myself?",
        faq_a18: "Absolutely. PassForge is 100% open-source. The entire codebase is available on GitHub. We encourage security researchers to audit the crypto implementation, key derivation, and memory handling. Transparency is our strongest defense.",
        faq_q19: "What about side-channel attacks (timing, power analysis)?",
        faq_a19: "PassForge uses constant-time comparison for password verification to prevent timing attacks. Power analysis and electromagnetic attacks require physical access and specialized equipment‚Äîthese are state-level threats beyond the scope of software-only defenses.",
        faq_q20: "Is PassForge vulnerable to SQL injection?",
        faq_a20: "No. All database queries use parameterized statements (prepared queries). User input is never directly concatenated into SQL strings. Additionally, since the database content is encrypted, even a hypothetical injection would only return encrypted blobs.",
        faq_q21: "Can I use PassForge on a shared/public computer?",
        faq_a21: "Not recommended. Shared computers may have keyloggers, screen recorders, or malware. If you must, use Tails OS (live USB), never save the vault file locally, and ensure the system is rebooted after use to clear RAM. Treat all shared systems as compromised.",
        faq_threat_notice: "‚ö†Ô∏è THREAT MODEL NOTICE: PassForge provides mid-level protection in its threat model. It defends against: casual attackers, malware, forensic analysis, and brute-force. It does NOT defend against: state-level adversaries with physical access, evil maid attacks, or compromised operating systems. For maximum security, use Tails + air-gapped devices.",

